{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1973"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1973"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.34,0.15,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111390"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1973"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93520"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"370"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45331"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111390"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy is presented to the Emergency Department by his parents, expressing concerns about the child\u0027s condition. The child has been experiencing high fever, noisy breathing, a distinctive barking cough, nasal discharge, and poor feeding for the past two days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the child feels warm to touch, diaphoretic, and is visibly distressed, displaying irritability and persistent crying. A provisional diagnosis of croup is given, and recognising the urgency of the presentation, the medical team is prepared to conduct a thorough assessment including measurement of the patient\u2019s core temperature.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method to measure the child\u2019s temperature in this clinical setting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axilla","Rectum","Forehead via infrared","Oesophageal","Nasopharynx"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe choice of site for measurement of a patient\u2019s body temperature is important, and should reflect either direct measurement or a reasonable estimation (within \u0026lt;0.5\u00baC) of the core body temperature. The recommended sites therefore include pulmonary artery (via a catheter), distal oesophagus, urinary bladder, deep forehead (via zero heat-flux thermometry), sublingual, axilla and rectum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second consideration in this setting is choosing the least invasive method of accurately recording the child\u0027s temperature given their presentation is consistent with croup (laryngotracheobronchitis). Upper airway obstruction worsens when children with croup are distressed and therefore invasive investigations or examinations should be avoided as it can rapidly worsen the child\u0027s clinical status. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary temperature \u003C/strong\u003Emeasurement provides a reasonable balance between accuracy and efficiency, and is widely accessible which makes obtaining a quick and accurate temperature reading easy especially in an emergency setting. The child is visibly distressed, irritable, and crying, indicating a high level of discomfort. Axillary temperature measurement is a non-invasive method that can be quickly and easily performed without causing additional distress to the child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeasurement of core temperature via the\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Erectum\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Eusing a rectal probe is a reliable method for obtaining core temperature, which can be performed rapidly and is widely available. Whilst in clinical practice rectal temperature is often performed in neonates, it is not the most suitable option in this case. Obtaining a rectal temperature can be challenging due to discomfort and resistance in a child of four years of age. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForehead via infrared\u003C/strong\u003E is a method widely used by GPs and parents at home. An infrared thermometer measures the temperature of the skin rather than the actual core temperature, which is imprecise and often shows a normal temperature despite an increased core temperature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal\u003C/strong\u003E temperature measurement involves inserting a probe into the oesophagus. This method is invasive and carries the risk of bronchospasm, making it unsuitable for the initial assessment of a child with respiratory distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasopharyngeal\u003C/strong\u003E temperature measurement is not suitable in this case due to the child\u0027s nasal discharge. The presence of discharge or obstruction of nasal canal may interfere with the accuracy of temperature readings, making this method impractical.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sites for good direct measure and an accurate estimate of core temperature include the pulmonary artery, distal oesophagus, urinary bladder, deep forehead, sublingual, axilla, and rectum.","Selection of an appropriate measurement site of core temperature depends on clinical circumstances."],"references":["Hypothermia: prevention and management in adults having surgery. In NICE: Clinical Guidelines, National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (UK). 2016. Accessed 2020 May 5. Available at: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg65.","Hymczak H, Go\u0142\u0105b A, Mendrala K, Plicner D, Darocha T, Podsiad\u0142o P, et al. Core Temperature Measurement-Principles of Correct Measurement, Problems, and Complications. Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2021 Oct 10;18(20):10606. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8535559/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93520"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1973"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93520"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T19:26:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T19:26:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1973"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111390"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data